        "papers": [
            {
                "s2_paper_id": "af4831fe06083af77a50685fe7fd13f6ae75f1e8",
                "title": "Professional development and instructional leadership: views and experiences of U.S. mathematics and science teachers who leave the classroom to lead",
                "year": 2025,
                "venue": "Journal of Education and Teaching",
                "citation_count": 2,
                "reference_count": 42,
                "abstract": "ABSTRACT This paper examines the perspectives and experiences of 21 science and mathematics teachers in the U.S. who shifted from classroom teaching to leadership roles in their schools and districts. These individuals viewed themselves as \u2018teacher leaders\u2019, regardless of whether they maintained classroom teaching responsibilities, and they engaged in work typically associated with researchers\u2019 definitions of teacher leaders. They viewed teacher leaders as learned and trusted collaborators who advocate on behalf of teachers and their schools for effective teaching and positive pupil outcomes. Thirteen of the 21 individuals participated in an extensive and intensive leadership development programme that they attribute to supporting and developing their capacities to lead by adding to their knowledge of mathematics and science content and pedagogy, providing leadership knowledge and practice opportunities, and establishing their confidence and awareness of themselves as leaders. Individuals who did not participate in the leadership programme did not report the same sense of empowerment and expanded professional horizons, but were more likely to report the importance and influence of a mentor in their journey towards leadership. This study contributes knowledge to the field about educational leadership development programmes and provides insight on teacher leadership from the perspectives of school science and mathematics teachers who shift into leadership roles.",
